    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_28853313" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/28853313" />
    <a title="Gabriel Conroy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1381954-gabriel-conroy"><img alt="Gabriel Conroy" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/28853313?book_show_action=true">Jul 31, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Gabriel Conroy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Gabriel Conroy" href="/user/show/1381954-gabriel-conroy">Gabriel Conroy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer28853313" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3576533294653189950">The protagonists of this play are Titus, the Roman emperor, and Berenice, the Queen of Judea. They face an impossible choice: to marry and incur the wrath of the Roman mob or to quit each other and live separate lives of hopeless desolation.<br/><br/>&quot;Dans un moi, dans un an, comment suffrirons nous,<br/>Seigneur, que tant de mars me separent de vous.&quot;<br/>(For one month, for one year, how will we manage,<br/>Sir, if so many seas keep you from me.)<br/><br/>Such is the dilemma as Berenice explains it to Titus. It is the 17th-cent</span>
  <span id="freeText3576533294653189950" style="display:none">The protagonists of this play are Titus, the Roman emperor, and Berenice, the Queen of Judea. They face an impossible choice: to marry and incur the wrath of the Roman mob or to quit each other and live separate lives of hopeless desolation.<br /><br />"Dans un moi, dans un an, comment suffrirons nous,<br />Seigneur, que tant de mars me separent de vous."<br />(For one month, for one year, how will we manage,<br />Sir, if so many seas keep you from me.)<br /><br />Such is the dilemma as Berenice explains it to Titus. It is the 17th-century French distinction between "amour-devoir" (love as a duty) and "amour-passion" (love as a sentiment).<br /><br />This is Racine at his finest: he sets up characters who face impossible choices. The choices dance perilously close to the thin line between the pathetic and the tragic: the characters are damned if they do and damned if they don't. In his other plays (at least the ones I've read), the development is less stark, as in "Britannicus" and "Iphigenie." ("Phedre," and even more so, the religious plays like "Bejazet" and "Esther," are the odd-plays out, and I'm not sure what to make of them.)<br /><br />Of Racine's plays, I'm not sure if I like Berenice or Andromaque better. Both plays remind me that old vision of the end of the world, noted in Robert Frost's distinction between "fire and ice" and echoed in T. S. Eliot's "The Hollow Men"<br /><br />"This is the way the world ends<br />Not with a bang but a whimper."<br /><br />In both plays, the main characters face a Hobson's choice: they can choose their own end: do they choose the bang or the whimper? In "Berenice," they choose one; in "Andromaque" they choose another. The result is the same.<br /><br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="3576533294653189950" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

